    scripture: "He hath made every thing beautiful in his time...",
    walk: `Just before this verse, friend, Solomon writes that famous passage: *to every thing there is a season... a time to weep, and a time to laugh; a time to mourn, and a time to dance.* Life has seasons, and not all of them are spring. Some are long, cold winters of weariness and waiting. And the weary heart often fears it's stuck in winter forever. But Solomon adds this hope: *He hath made every thing beautiful in his time.*

Notice he doesn't say everything *is* beautiful right now, or that every season *feels* good while you're in it. He says God *makes* it beautiful — *in his time.* There's a craftsmanship here, a patient work God is doing across the seasons of your life, weaving even the hard and weary ones into something beautiful that you can't fully see yet. The winter season isn't a mistake or a waste. In the hands of God, it's part of a beauty still being formed, on a timetable that is His, not yours.

That phrase — *in his time* — asks something of the weary, friend: trust. Trust that the season you're in has a purpose, that it has an end, and that God is working even now to make it beautiful, even if today you only see the bareness of winter. The same God who appoints the seasons of nature appoints the seasons of your life, and He has never yet failed to bring spring after winter. Hold on through your season. He is making something beautiful, in His time, and it will be worth the wait.`,
    prayer: `Father, this season has felt like a long winter, and I've feared I'm stuck here for good. But You make everything beautiful in Your time. Help me trust that even this weary season has purpose and an end, that You are weaving it into something beautiful I can't yet see. Give me patience to wait for Your timing, and faith that spring always follows winter in Your hands. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
