    walk: `Here's a turn in the road you might not expect, friend. As God renews your strength, He doesn't intend for it to stop with you. Isaiah speaks of having *the tongue of the learned... to speak a word in season to him that is weary.* One of the most beautiful things God does with the renewed is to make them a source of renewal for others. The very weariness you've walked through becomes the thing that lets you speak life to someone else who's worn down.

There's deep healing in this, friend. Sometimes the way out of your own weariness is to lift the weariness of another. When you reach out to encourage someone else who's struggling — to *speak a word in season to him that is weary* — something stirs back to life in your own soul. The comfort you've received from God becomes comfort you can pass along. Paul put it this way: God comforts us in all our tribulation, *that we may be able to comfort them which are in any trouble, by the comfort wherewith we ourselves are comforted of God.* Your hard road wasn't wasted. It equipped you.

And notice the gentleness of it: *a word in season.* Not a sermon, not a fix, not advice from on high. Just the right word at the right time — *I see you. You're not alone. God hasn't forgotten you. I've been there too, and He carried me through.* You know exactly what that word means because you've needed it yourself. So as God renews you, friend, look around. There's someone near you who's weary right where you once were, and you may be the very one God sends to speak that word in season. The weary, renewed by God, become His messengers of hope to other weary hearts.`,
